We present a case of a giant mycotic aneurysm of the left internal carotid 
artery in a child, the result of direct extension of a deep neck space 
infection. This lesion is life threatening and may put the patient at risk of 
unwarranted biopsy or drainage if not recognized. Diagnosis and treatment 
planning rely heavily on cross-sectional imaging, and angiography is frequently 
necessary. This case is unique for two reasons: (1) we present for the first 
time the MRI findings and (2) we describe an alternative to surgical ligation -- 
neurointerventional embolotherapy. Minimally invasive transcatheter embolization 
was successfully performed on our patient to occlude the abnormal left internal 
carotid artery segment.

